In Southern regions, this variety is resistant to root and crown disease, unlike the regular species. Exotic white flowers with yellow-orange markings appear on tall stalks. The flowers seldom set seedpods, resulting in a prolonged bloom period. Improved foliage is a brighter green with wider and longer leaf blades. A portion of the proceeds benefits the America's Wetlands Foundation, helping to restore wetlands in Louisiana.</PlantBenefits>

		<CareInstructions>Best in light shade in inland areas. Provide well-drained soil, rich in organic matter. 		<PriAttribute>Year-round Interest</PriAttribute>
		<AvgLandscapeSize>Fast growing to 18 to 24 in. tall and wide</AvgLandscapeSize>
		<CareInstructions>Best in light shade in hot, inland areas. Provide well-drained soil, rich in organic matter. Follow a regular watering schedule during the first growing season to establish a deep, extensive root system. Feed occasionally with a slow release fertilizer. For a neat appearance, remove older foliage when new growth appears. Clumps may be divided very 2 to 3 years in early spring.</CareInstructions>
		<ContainerSize>1</ContainerSize>
		<LegalVolume>3 qt. (2.84 L)</LegalVolume>
		<UPC>014949357033</UPC>
		<FlowerTime>Spring</FlowerTime>
		<PlantBenefits>Handsome strappy green leaves with contrasting white stripes will brighten up the garden year-round. Neat clumping habit is ideal for mass planting in garden beds and borders. Delicate sprays of pale blue-violet flowers are produced on fine stems above the foliage in mid spring. Bright blue berries follow in summer. Best suited to warmer climates. Evergreen.</PlantBenefits>
		<SunExpose>Partial to full sun</SunExpose>
		<WaterReq>Once established, needs only occasional watering. In warmer inland areas, water more often in extreme heat.</WaterReq>
		<CZoneHigh>11</CZoneHigh>
		<CZoneLow>7</CZoneLow>

		<SunExpose>Full sun</SunExpose>
		<WaterReq>Needs regular watering - weekly, or more often in extreme heat.</WaterReq>

		<CZoneLow>10</CZoneLow>

		<FlowerTime>Spring through fall</FlowerTime>
		<PlantBenefits>Hanging clusters of scarlet tubular flowers resembling small firecrackers cover this plant from spring through fall. Its slender, rushlike stems are coverded with small scales. Wiry branches start out erect then fall over into long cascades. A favorite of hummingbirds and a must have for tropical butterfly gardens, it is often grown in hanging baskets, spilling over walls, or tied to a trellis.</PlantBenefits>
		<SunExpose>Partial shade to full sun</SunExpose>
		<WaterReq>Water regularly, when top 3 in. of soil is dry.</WaterReq>
